SIMPLE: profane
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Profane
<hw>Pro*fane"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>profanus</ets>, properly, before the temple, i. e., without the
temple, unholy; <ets>pro</ets> before + <ets>fanum</ets> temple. See 1st
<er>Fane</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Not sacred or holy; not possessing peculiar
sanctity; unconsecrated; hence, relating to matters other than sacred;
secular; -- opposed to <xex>sacred</xex>, <xex>religious</xex>, or
<xex>inspired</xex>; <as>as, a <ex>profane</ex> place</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Profane</xex> authors.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>I.
Disraeli.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>profane</qex> wreath was suspended before the shrine.</q>
<rj><qau>Gibbon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unclean; impure; polluted; unholy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing is <qex>profane</qex> that serveth to holy things.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Treating sacred things with contempt, disrespect,
irreverence, or undue familiarity; irreverent; impious.</def> Hence,
specifically; <def>Irreverent in language; taking the name of God in
vain; given to swearing; blasphemous; <as>as, a <ex>profane</ex> person,
word, oath, or tongue</as>.</def> <au>1 Tim. i. 9.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Secular; temporal; worldly; unsanctified;
unhallowed; unholy; irreligious; irreverent; ungodly; wicked; godless;
impious. See <er>Impious</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Profane</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Profane
<hw>Pro*fane"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Profaned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Profaning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>profanare</ets>: cf.
F. <ets>profaner</ets>. See <er>Profane</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To violate, as anything sacred; to treat with abuse,
irreverence, obloquy, or contempt; to desecrate; to pollute; <as>as, to
<ex>profane</ex> the name of God; to <ex>profane</ex> the Scriptures, or
the ordinance of God.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The priests in the temple <qex>profane</qex> the sabbath.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. xii. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put to a wrong or unworthy use; to make a base
employment of; to debase; to abuse; to defile.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So idly to <qex>profane</qex> the precious time.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Profanely</ent>⟦br⟧
